  <data name="FullDescription" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>A single identity that is asserted by flows from two or more distinct sources is a shared, static principal. When several callers present the same identity (the same certificate, token, or subject), the identity's authorization has to cover everything every caller needs, so each caller receives an over-broad token — and a compromise of one caller cannot be distinguished from the others (spoofing and elevation of privilege).

This rule is violated when the same non-empty Identity value is declared on flows that originate from two or more distinct sources. It does not fire for a single principal that reuses its own identity across several of its own flows.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="HelpText" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Give each calling principal its own identity instead of one shared, static identity. Set a distinct Identity (and a least-privilege TokenScope) on each caller's flow so the token or certificate issued to one caller cannot be presented by another.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="MessageText" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>The {0} asserts the shared identity '{1}', which is presented by {2} distinct sources; give each principal its own scoped identity so no caller receives an over-broad token.</value>
